{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox Hurricane | Name=Late November 1984 Nor'easter/Tropical Depression 19 | Type=Tropical depression | Year=1984 | Basin=Atl | Image location=Surface analysis of cyclone November 23, 1984.jpg | Image name=Image of the storm while at its most intense at 1&nbsp;pm EST November 23, 1984. Its well-defined cold front is seen entering eastern [[Cuba]] at that time. | Formed=November 22, 1984 | Dissipated=December 1, 1984 | Extratropical=November 29, 1984 | 1-min winds=30 | Pressure=1005 | Damages=7.4 | Inflated=0 | Fatalities=1 | Areas=[[The Bahamas]], [[Florida]], [[Bermuda]] | Hurricane season=[[1984 Atlantic hurricane season]] }}
The '''Late November 1984 [[Nor'easter]]''' occurred on the United States' [[Thanksgiving|Thanksgiving Day]], November 22, 1984. A deep [[extratropical cyclone]] located just off the shore of Florida led to significant beach erosion and the grounding of the freighter ''Mercedes I'' for several months along the coastal town of [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]].<ref>Vanderbilt University Television News Archive. [http://tvnews.vanderbilt.edu/program.pl?ID=87852 Headline: Florida / Grounded Freighter.] Retrieved on November 18, 2006.</ref> It formed unusually early, and its effects were seen unusually far south into Florida.
==Meteorological history== When a cyclone aloft cut off from the main band of the [[Westerlies]], it spurred [[cyclogenesis]] in the [[Florida Straits]] by November 22, which led to a [[nor'easter]] at an unusually southern latitude near the [[Bahamas]]. The surface cyclone slowly traveled through the [[Florida Straits]] up the [[Gulf Stream]] between Florida and the Bahamas before drifting back out to sea. The storm attempted to gain some central convection during several periods of its life cycle. It was at its most intense on November 23 and November 24, with a central pressure near 1005&nbsp;[[pascal (unit)|hPa]].<ref>U.S. Department of Commerce. [http://docs.lib.noaa.gov/rescue/dwm/1984/19841119-19841125.djvu Daily Weather Maps: November 19- November 25, 1984.] Retrieved on November 18, 2006.</ref> The cyclone moved far enough to the east to allow winds and seas to subside on November 26. There is some evidence that it may have become a subtropical cyclone around November 28, while located in the vicinity of [[Bermuda]].<ref>Danielle Manning and Robert Hart. [http://ams.confex.com/ams/pdfpapers/108582.pdf Using ERA40 in Cyclone Phase Space to Refine the Classification of Historical Tropical Storms.] Retrieved on November 18, 2006.</ref> This is why the system is considered the 19th tropical depression of the 1984 Atlantic hurricane season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/hurdat/newhurdat-all.html|title=HURDAT2 Atlantic Hurricane Database|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]|author=[[Hurricane Research Division]]|date=November 2012|accessdate=November 24, 2012}}</ref>
{{clear}} ==Effects== [[File:Nor'easter 1984-11-23 weather map.gif|thumb|right|Surface analysis showing the cyclone on the morning of November 23, 1984]] Significant rainfall was recorded along the [[Palm Beach County, Florida|Palm Beach County]] coast between November 21 and November 26 during this event,<ref>Wossenu Abtew, R. Scott Huebner, and Violeta Ciuca. South Florida Water Management District. [http://www.sfwmd.gov/sfer/SFER_2006/volume1/chapters/v1_ch_5.pdf Chapter 5: Hydrology of the South Florida Environment.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928231142/http://www.sfwmd.gov/sfer/SFER_2006/volume1/chapters/v1_ch_5.pdf |date=September 28, 2006 }} Retrieved on November 18, 2006.</ref> with local amounts of up to {{convert|11.29|in|mm}} measured at [[West Palm Beach, Florida]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wpc.ncep.noaa.gov/research/roth/noreaster1984filledrainblk.gif|title=November 1984 Nor'easter Storm Total Rainfall Graphic|author=David M. Roth|publisher=[[Hydrometeorological Prediction Center]]|date=November 24, 2012|accessdate=November 24, 2012}}</ref> Surface temperatures hovered in the middle 50s°F, or around 13°C, within the main region of impact. However, wind and high seas were the storm's main impact due to the strong pressure gradient between the cyclone's center and a 1040&nbsp;hPa surface high over the [[Ohio Valley]]. Winds as high as {{convert|58|mph|km/h}} with swells of up to {{convert|20|ft|m}} were reported by ships in the eastern [[Gulf of Mexico]]. Along the Atlantic coast, winds reached {{convert|58|mph|km/h}} at [[Vero Beach, Florida|Vero Beach]], {{convert|55|mph|km/h}} at [[Melbourne, Florida|Melbourne]], {{convert|46|mph|km/h}} at [[Titusville, Florida|Titusville]], and {{convert|44|mph|km/h}} at [[Cocoa Beach, Florida|Cocoa Beach]]. Offshore the Atlantic coast, seas also reached {{convert|20|ft|m}}. Coastal erosion took its toll between [[St. Augustine, Florida|St. Augustine]] and Palm Beach during the three-day storm, which eventually subsided on November 26. About five-sixths of a new pier at St. Augustine was destroyed. Erosion from this cyclone would be the worst experienced in southern [[Brevard County, Florida|Brevard County]] until [[Hurricane Frances]] in 2004.<ref>Florida Department of Environmental Protection. [http://bcs.dep.state.fl.us/reports/franjean/Hurricanes_Frances_&_Jeanne/Report_Sections/East_Coast/Brevard_County.pdf Brevard County: Hurricane Frances and Jeanne Damage Assessment Location Map.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721150744/http://bcs.dep.state.fl.us/reports/franjean/Hurricanes_Frances_%26_Jeanne/Report_Sections/East_Coast/Brevard_County.pdf |date=July 21, 2011 }} Retrieved on November 19, 2006.</ref>
The storm dragged the 197-foot Venezuelan freighter ''Mercedes I'' ashore the coast of Palm Beach and through a [[seawall]], where it remained in a socialite's backyard into early 1985.<ref>Marc Fisher and Mary Jo Tierney, Miami Herald. [http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MH&s_site=miami&p_multi=MH&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB36113B5B040D4&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM STORM CUTS SWATH OF DESTRUCTION ALONG FLORIDA COAST.] Retrieved on November 18, 2006.</ref> Once hauled out to sea, the vessel was sunk and became an artificial coral reef off Fort Lauderdale on March 30, 1985.<ref>Greg Johnston. [http://www.visitflorida.com/cms/d/exploring_wrecks_in_fort_lauderdale_and_the_keys.php Exploring Wrecks in Fort Lauderdale and the Keys.] Retrieved on November 18, 2006.</ref> A second freighter ran aground offshore [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]]. Damage from Vero Beach alone totalled US$3.4&nbsp;million (1984&nbsp;dollars). [[Martin County, Florida|Martin County]] reported an addition US$4&nbsp;million in losses (1984&nbsp;dollars).<ref>The New York Times. United Press International. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05E7D61638F935A15752C1A962948260 AROUND THE NATION; Florida's Storm Ends, Leaving Damage Behind.] Retrieved on November 18, 2006.</ref> One person perished.<ref>National Weather Service Forecast Office, Melbourne, Florida. [http://www.srh.weather.gov/mlb/mart.html Martin County.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041119202418/http://www.srh.weather.gov/mlb/mart.html |date=November 19, 2004 }} Retrieved on November 19, 2006.</ref>
{{clear}}
==Other significant Florida extratropical cyclones== [[File:Noreaster1984filledrainblk.gif|thumb|right|Rainfall from the Late November 1984 Florida Nor'easter across Florida and Georgia]] The top three deadliest tornado outbreaks in the state's history occurred with extratropical cyclones in February 1998, March 1962, and April 1966.<ref>Bartlett C. Hagemeyer and Scott M. Spratt. [http://www.srh.weather.gov/mlb/agnes30.html THIRTY YEARS AFTER HURRICANE AGNES - THE FORGOTTEN FLORIDA TORNADO DISASTER.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061228210047/http://www.srh.weather.gov/mlb/agnes30.html |date=December 28, 2006 }} Retrieved on November 25, 2006.</ref> In 1989, a December cyclone spun up offshore northeast Florida, bringing measureable snow to Jacksonville and flurries across [[Sarasota, Florida|Sarasota]] in west-central Florida,<ref>National Weather Service Forecast Office, Melbourne, Florida. [http://www.srh.weather.gov/mlb/surveys/012403/flurries.html Cold Temperatures and Snow Flurries in East-Central Florida January 24, 2003.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928232856/http://www.srh.weather.gov/mlb/surveys/012403/flurries.html |date=September 28, 2006 }} Retrieved on November 19, 2006.</ref> and some [[Lake Okeechobee]]-[[Lake-effect snow|effect]] snows downwind of the lake. In 1993, the [[1993 North American storm complex|Storm of the Century]] brought an intense squall line, and winds gusting over {{convert|100|mph|km/h}}, to much of the Sunshine State during the early morning hours of March 13. Later that day, flurries were witnessed across the [[Florida Panhandle]] in its wake. A frontal wave which became a powerful [[Christmas 1994 Nor'easter]] moved across Florida, bringing windy and rainy conditions to the state.
==See also== *[[Climate of Florida]] *[[Extratropical cyclone]] *[[Surface weather analysis]]
