{{Infobox motorsport championship | name = V de V Challenge Monoplace | logo = | image-size = | caption = | category = Single seater | country = | region = Europe | inaugural = 2010 | inaugural2 = | folded = | classes = | drivers = | riders = | teams = | constructors = | manufacturers = | engines = | tyres = | tires = | current_champions = | champion driver = {{flagicon|ARG}} Nicolás Varrone | champion rider = | champion team = TS Corse | manufacturer = | constructor = | website = [http://www.vdev.fr/category/challenge-monoplace Official website] | current_season = 2018 V de V Challenge Monoplace }}
The '''V de V Challenge Monoplace''' is a single-seater racing series active in Europe. The series was founded in 2010 set up by [[V de V Sports]].
==History== The series was founded in 2010 and originally divided into three sub classes. The series saw the light as the [[Tatuus]] FR2000, which was abundant in Europe, was replaced by the [[Barazi-Epsilon]] FR2.0-10 in various [[Formula Renault]] series. The Tatuus FR2000 formed Class A along with 1990-2007 [[Formula 3]] cars and [[Van Diemen]] [[Formula X]] cars. During the inaugural season only Tatuus FR2000 competed in Class A. Class B was open for the Tatuus FR1600, 1995-1999 Formula Renault cars, [[Formula Ford Zetec]] cars and [[Formula Renault Campus]]. Finally, Class C was open for [[Formula BMW]] and other single seaters with a motorbike engine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Monoplace >> Challenge MONOPLACE |url=http://www.vdev.fr/monospace_challenge.html |website=V de V |accessdate=18 December 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304113449/http://www.vdev.fr/monospace_challenge.html |archivedate=4 March 2010 |df= }}</ref>
The inaugural race was run at [[Circuit de Haute Saingonge]] near [[La Genétouze, Charente-Maritime]]. Experienced gentleman racer [[Philippe Haezebrouck]] won Class A and the overall championship. As of 2011 the [[Tatuus N.T07]] was accepted in the series. The car previously raced in the [[International Formula Master]] between 2007 [[International Formula Master|2007]] and [[2009 International Formula Master|2009]]. The car formed Class A along with older Formula 3 chassis. The Tatuus FR2000 was relegated into Class B along with Formula X. Grids grew in the sophomore season as the series visited Spain for the first time, at [[Circuito del Jarama|Jarama]] and [[Ciudad del Motor de Aragón|Motorland Aragon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Single-seater >> SINGLE-SEATER V de V Challenge |url=http://www.vdev.fr/singleseater_challenge.html |website=V de V |accessdate=18 December 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920040845/http://www.vdev.fr/singleseater_challenge.html |archivedate=20 September 2011 |df= }}</ref> Young [[Simon Gachet]] won Class B and the overall championship, as it was still the most abundant car in the field. For 2012 the class rules were again amended with the [[Scuderia Coloni|Coloni]] CN1/98 [[1998 Euro Open by Nissan|Formula Nissan]] added to Class A. [[Hugo Blanchot]] won the overall championship scored ten podium finishes in fifteen races.<ref>{{cite web|title=Single-seater V de V Challenge 2012 standings|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/single-seater-v-de-v-challenge/2012/|website=DriverDB.com|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> For 2013 the Tatuus FR2000 was further relegated into Class C. As the [[Barazi-Epsilon]] FR2.0-10 was replaced by the Tatuus FR 2.0-13 the car was accepted in Class B. Tatuus [[Formula Abarth]] chassis were also added to Class C. [[John Filippi]] won the overall championship in a Tatuus N.T07 as the Baraz-Epsilon car became more prominent but was not as fast at the Tatuus.
As of 2014 also current spec Formula Renault cars were allowed by the V de V organisation, starting with the Tatuus FR 2.0-13. The car was allowed in Class A as Formula Master cars and Formula 3 cars were no longer allowed. Italian driver [[Daniele Cazzaniga]] won the series in 2014 with eight 2013 spec Formula Renault cars filling the top ten. The following season the class distribution remained the same with [[David Droux]] winning the overall championship.
